<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920117-0161</DOCNO><DOCID>920117-0161.</DOCID><HL>   Ex-Southmark Aide,   Grosz, Pleads Innocent   To U.S. Fraud Charges</HL><DATE>01/17/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5</SO><CO>   SMRK</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)REAL ESTATE INVESTMENTS (REA)SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS (SAL)</IN><NS>BANKRUPTCY DECLARATIONS AND PROCEEDINGS (BCY)</NS><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)TEXAS (TX)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   DALLAS -- Joseph Grosz, a former executive at twoSouthmark Corp. units, pleaded innocent to U.S. charges ofconspiracy and bank fraud related to loans from a thrift thatSouthmark owned.   Mr. Grosz, a Chicago resident, is scheduled to go on trialMarch 2 before U.S. District Judge Robert B. Maloney here.Mr. Grosz is accused of authorizing the now-defunct SanJacinto Savings Association to make $43.5 million inartificially inflated loans to a borrower who allegedlyreturned $1.6 million of the funds to a company partiallyowned by Mr. Grosz.</LP><TEXT>   Mr. Grosz previously served as senior vice president ofSan Jacinto Savings and as president of Southmark Funding,another unit of Dallas-based Southmark. His indictment onDec. 11 was the first to arise from an investigation ofSouthmark and San Jacinto Savings by the U.S. JusticeDepartment's Dallas Bank Fraud Task Force.   The 12 charges against Mr. Grosz carry a maximum penaltyof 60 years in prison and a $3 million fine.</TEXT></DOC>